For PbBr2 NS growth, a new island will nucleate firstly on a facet of the sheet. When reaching a critical size, this island will then become stable and will acquire a driving force to expand, and finally a new adlayer will be added to the facet itself  31,32. Inspection of the as-prepared NS reveals the presence of layered structures on the surface of the NS (Fig. 2b). These atomically thin NSs can only survive on top of the NSs, they tend to break or aggregate in the solution. The thinnest NS estimated from the AFM observations is determined to be 0.5 nm, which correspond to a monolayer (Fig. 2c). These top layers are likely to be generated by two-dimensional nucleation, which then spread and merge to cover the surface. The planar structure of the NSs demonstrates that the growth rate of out-of-plane is much lower than that in-plane due to the distinct surface energies in different directions. In general, the surface energy along the in-plane direction is expected to be lower than that out of plane, thus leading to a faster planar growth rate. The surface stability can be evaluated by assessing the following quantity:σd=12A(Eslab−Ebulk)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
